Generalized Pareto Distribution (GPD) Models

Extreme value modeling and asymptotic motivation for the GPD

\(\text{GPD}(\sigma,\xi)\) CDF .

\[ \begin{equation} F_{>u}(x) = 1 - \Bigg\{ 1+ \xi \Bigg( \frac{x-u}{\sigma} \Bigg) \Bigg\}^{-\frac{1}{\xi}}, \qquad{\text{ for } x>u,} \end{equation} \] where

  • \(u\) is the threshold for fitting and

  • \(\sigma>0\): scale parameter

  • \(\xi \in \mathbb{R}\): shape parameter.

GPD \(u\) .

GPD range .

  • \(\xi <0\) \(u<x\leq u-\frac{\sigma}{\xi}\)

  • \(\xi\geq 0\) \(u<x<\infty\)

  • \(\xi=0\) GPD Exponential distn .

Extreme value theory threshold excesses normalisation limiting distn generalized Pareto family .

Parameterization

GPD scale parameter \(\sigma\), shape parameter \(\xi\) texmex \(\sigma\) \(\phi=\log \sigma\) .

  • \(\phi\)

  • \(\sigma>0\)

  • prior distn Gaussian \(\sigma\) \(\phi\) Gaussian .

Threshold selection

GPD threshold . texmex mean residual life (MRL) plot threshold stability plot .

########################################
#Generalized Pareto distribution models
########################################
########################################
#Threshold selection
########################################
grfRain <- gpdRangeFit(rain,umax=35) 
mrlRain <- mrl(rain)

g1 <- ggplot(grfRain) 
g2 <- ggplot(mrlRain)

grid.arrange(g1[[1]] + ggtitle("Stability plot, scale parameter"), 
             g1[[2]] + ggtitle("Stability plot, shape parameter"), 
             g2 + ggtitle("MRL plot"),ncol=2)

\(\log \hat{\sigma}\), \(\hat{\xi}\) threshold stability plot, MRL . threshold stability plot threshold 20 stable . MRL plot threshold 60 , heavy tail, positive shape parameter .

Note that this form of MRL plot is typical, with the very highest thresholds giving very erratic estimates with apparently narrow confidence bands. This commonly observed feature is due to the estimates for very high thresholds being based on a very small number of points.

\(97\)-th percentile candidate threshold .

quantile(rain, 0.97)
##  97% 
## 20.6

Maximum penalized likelihood estimation

Sample size GPD log=likelihood flat . penalized method . Experience suggests that the main problems may be overcome by putting fairly modest penalties on \(\xi\).

, log-likelihood \(l(\phi, \xi | X)\) \[l(\phi, \xi | X)$-\lambda \xi^{2}\] penalized version .

\(\lambda\)

, exponential \[L(\phi,\xi|X)e^{-\frac{\xi^2}{2\theta^2}}\] . \(\theta = \sqrt{\frac{1}{2\lambda}}\) . \(e^{-\frac{\xi^2}{2\theta^2}}\) 0 , mle Bayesian . (and corresponds to maximum a posteriori estimation)

GPD \(\xi=-1\) distn uniform, \(\xi=0\) exponential, \(\xi=1\) heavy-tail \(\infty\) . \(\xi=-1\), \(\xi=1\) implausible( ), \(\xi\) fairly close to 0 . prior distn 0 standard deviation \(\theta=\frac{1}{2}\) Gaussian .
